{"title_page": "White Coomb", "text_new": "{{about|the Scottish hill|the English hill|White Combe}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = White Coomb\n| photo = WhiteCoomb.jpg\n| photo_caption = White Coomb and Loch Skeen from the east\n| elevation_m = 821\n| elevation_ref = \n| prominence_m = 374\n| prominence_ref = \n| listing = [[Marilyn (hill)|Ma]],Hu,Tu,Sim,[[List of Corbett mountains in Scotland|C]],[[Donald (hill)|D]],CoH,DN,Y <ref>{{cite web|author=Chris Crocker |url=http://www.hills-database.co.uk/database_notes.html#classification |title=Database of British and Irish Hills: user guide |publisher=Hills-database.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n| location = [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Moffat Hills]], [[Southern Uplands]]\n| coordinates = \n| grid_ref_UK = NT 16321 15090\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 79\n| map =\n}}\n\n'''White Coomb''' is a hill in the [[Moffat Hills]] range, part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of [[Scotland]]. The ridges are broad, but are defended by steep valleys. Its summit is the highest point of the range and the [[registration county]] of [[Dumfriesshire|Dumfries]].\n\nWhite Coomb is most easily climbed from the [[National Trust for Scotland]] car park underneath the [[Grey Mare's Tail, Moffat Hills|Grey Mare's Tail]] waterfall, on the A708 from [[Moffat]] to [[Selkirk, Scottish Borders|Selkirk]], at NT 186146. The most direct route heads directly west up a steep ridge, but a more comfortable route follows a well built footpath above the north side of the waterfall. Above the waterfall, the fast flowing Tail Burn must be crossed to avoid a long detour; although there are plenty of natural stepping stones, spate or icy conditions may make their use dangerous. From across the stream, the best route through the peat and heather follows the course of a wall leading to the summit of Upper Tarnberry (546 m). From there, the east ridge, which is steep and craggy in places, leads to the broad summit.\n\nAn alternative ascent, described by the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' as one of \"Britain's finest half-day and day walks\", follows the Tail Burn to the outlet of [[Loch Skeen]] before ascending the ridge to Mid Craig, and passing Donald's Cleuch Head to reach the summit. The descent suggested is via Rough Craig and south to join the road and walk back to the start point.<ref>{{ cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/picturegalleries/6231584/Britains-finest-half-day-and-day-walks-with-maps.html?image=17 | title = Britain's finest half-day and day walks: 18. Loch Skeen and White Coomb | work = [[Daily Telegraph]] | location=London | date=25 September 2009| accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref>  \n \n==Subsidiary summits==\nThe Database of British and Irish hills<ref name=dbih>{{cite web|title=Database of British and Irish Hills|url=http://www.hills-database.co.uk/downloads.html|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref>  lists 18 subsidiary summits of White Coomb.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Summit !! Height (m) !! Drop (m) !! Grid ref !! Notes<ref>Abbreviations used: C = [[Corbett (hill)|Corbett]], CoH = County Top - Historic, CTC = Corbett Top of Corbett, D = [[Donald (hill)|Donald]], Ma = [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]], GTC = [[Graham (hill)|Graham]] Top of Corbett, Hu = [[Hill lists in the British Isles#Others|HuMP]], sGT= sub-Graham Top, sHu = sub-HuMP, xGT = deleted Graham Top</ref>\n|-\n| White Coomb || 821 || 374 || NT163150 || Ma,C,D,CoH, cairn\n|-\n| [[Cape Law]] || 722 || 93 || NT131150 || D,GTC,sHu, fence corner\n|-\n| Carlavin Hill || 736 || 23 || NT142188 || DT,sGT, \n|-\n| Carrifran Gans || 757 || 42 || NT159138 || GTC,DT, no feature\n|-\n| Din Law || 667 || 53 || NT124157 || GTC,DT, small cairn\n|-\n| Ellers Cleuch Rig || 610 || 7 || NT126166 || xDT, no feature\n|-\n| [[Erie Hill]] || 690 || 92 || NT124187 || D,GTC,sHu, cairn\n|-\n| Firthhope Rig || 800 || 26 || NT153153 || DT,sCT, no feature\n|-\n| Firthybrig Head || 764 || 7 || NT158171 || 