{"title_page": "David Lowery (musician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                  = David Lowery\n| image                 = David Lowery.jpg\n| background            = solo_singer\n| birth_name            = David Charles Lowery\n| alias                 = \n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|1960|9|10}}\n| birth_place           = [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Texas]]<br />[[United States]]\n| death_date            = \n| instrument            = [[Singing|Vocals]]<br/>[[Guitar]]\n| genre                 = [[Alternative rock]], [[southern rock]], [[alternative country]], [[country music|country]]\n| occupation            = Lecturer UG\n| years_active          = 1983\u2013present\n| label                 = [[429 Records|429]] \n| associated_acts       = [[Camper Van Beethoven]]<br />[[Cracker (band)|Cracker]]\n| Education             = Doctorate  5-4-18  University of Georgia\n| website               = \n}}\n\n'''David Charles Lowery''' (born September 10, 1960) is an [[United States|American]] guitarist, vocalist, songwriter, and mathematician. He is the founder of [[alternative rock]] band [[Camper Van Beethoven]] and co-founder of the more-traditional rock band [[Cracker (band)|Cracker]]. Lowery released his first solo album, ''The Palace Guards'', on February 2, 2011, via the [[429 Records]] label.<ref name=\"429 Records1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.429records.com/sites/429records/aboutus.asp|title=About Us|year=2013|work=429 Records imprint from The Savoy Label Group (SLG), a division of Columbia Music Entertainment|publisher=429 Records Santa Monica. CA|accessdate=7 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618185217/http://www.429records.com/sites/429records/aboutus.asp|archive-date=18 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Personal life and music career===\nLowery was born in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Texas]], the son of a career [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] father. He has described his parents as \"a hillbilly and an English working-class woman.\"<ref name=fricke>{{cite magazine |last1=Fricke |first1=David |author-link1=David Fricke|date=19 May 1988|title=Camper Van Beethoven's Notes from the Underground |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/camper-van-beethovens-notes-from-the-underground-82927/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=8 November 2018 }}</ref> His family moved around a great deal during his youth before finally settling in [[Redlands, California]], where he attended high school. He became involved in music as a member of the band Sitting Ducks, who played a mixture of [[punk rock|punk]] and [[acid rock]], along with what Lowery described as \"fake Russian-sounding music.\" Sitting Ducks subsequently evolved into Camper Van Beethoven, formed in 1983 in [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/david-lowery-mn0000808839/biography | title=David Lowery | work=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=28 March 2014 | author=Deming, Mark}}</ref><ref name=fricke /> The band is best known for its cover of the [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]] song \"[[Pictures of Matchstick Men]]\" from the ''[[Key Lime Pie (album)|Key Lime Pie]]'' LP and its original composition \"[[Take the Skinheads Bowling]],\" from the band's 1985 debut LP, ''[[Telephone Free Landslide Victory]],'' later featured in the [[Michael Moore]] movie ''[[Bowling for Columbine]].''\n\nIn the early 1990s, Lowery formed Cracker with guitarist and long-time friend [[Johnny Hickman]] and bassist [[Davey Faragher]]. Cracker rejected the indie-rock sound of Camper Van Beethoven in favor of a more traditional, roots-rock sound. Cracker's biggest hits are \"Teen Angst (What the World Needs Now)\" from its [[Cracker (album)|eponymous LP]], released in 1992, and \"Low,\" from 1993's ''[[Kerosene Hat]].'' Cracker continues to perform today, although Camper Van Beethoven has also reformed, releasing a cover of the entire [[Fleetwood Mac]] album ''[[Tusk (album)|Tusk]]'' in 2002 and several new albums of original music, beginning with ''[[New Roman Times]]'' in 2004.\n\n[[File:David Lowery 03.jpg|thumb|left|David Lowery attending a book reading in 2011]]\nLowery has also done work as a producer at [[Sound of Music Studios]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]], working on records by [[Sparklehorse]], [[Counting Crows]], [[Lauren Hoffman]], [[September 67]], [[Wormburner]], [[LP (singer)|LP]], [[Tea Leaf Green]], [[Magnet (musician)|Magnet]], [[Sons of Bill]] and others. Lowery, along with Ian Solla-Yates of [[WNRN]] started RadioVA with Sound of Music in May 2010, an interview program hosted by David that has featured [[The Hold Steady]], [[Drive-By Truckers]], [[Minus the Bear]] and [[Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros]].\n\nOn September 13, 2010, David married Velena Vego. Vego has been the manager for both Cracker and Camper Van Beethoven since 2004. She is also the talent booker for the [[40 Watt Club]] in Athens, Georgia, and [[Buckhead Theatre]] in Atlanta.\n\n=== Other activities ===\nLowery is a trained [[mathematician]] who has worked as a \"[[quantitative analyst|quant]]\" (a [[derivative (finance)|derivatives]] trader and [[financial analyst]]) and has started a number of music-related businesses, including a [[recording studio|studio]], a [[record company]] and a [[Music publisher (popular music)|publishing company]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://thetrichordist.wordpress.com/2012/04/15/meet-the-new-boss-worse-than-the-old-boss-full-post/\n| work=The Trichordist\n| title=Meet the New Boss, Worse Than the Old Boss\n| date=April 15, 2012\n}}</ref>\nLowery's extensive experience in business led to his appointment as a lecturer in the [[University of Georgia]]'s music business program.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |last        = Miller\n |first       = Chris\n |date        = February 1, 2011\n |title       = TAKING NOTES: Rock star becomes University music professor\n |url         = http://www.redandblack.com/2011/02/01/taking-notes-rockstar-becomes-university-music-professor/\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110205125321/http://www.redandblack.com/2011/02/01/taking-notes-rockstar-becomes-university-music-professor/\n |archivedate = 2011-02-05\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/188835-cracker-berkeley-to-bakersfield-2495579662.html: \" in addition to this work, Lowery teaches as a lecturer and, as already mentioned, has a consistently high profile in the media as a champion of artists' rights. As such, it could almost be said that Lowery has become the voice of a generation\"|title=PopMatters|last=Pitter|first=Charles|website=PopMatters}}</ref>\n\nLowery earned a PhD from the University of Georgia in 2018<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lowery |first1=David |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/davidclowery |title=LinkedIn||website=LinkedIn |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>. Charles Pitter at PopMatters has said that \"in addition to this work, Lowery teaches as a lecturer and has a consistently high profile in the media as a champion of artists rights. As such, it could almost be said that Lowery has become the voice of a generation; however, it seems likely he would dismiss this title as meaningless blabber.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/188835-cracker-berkeley-to-bakersfield-2495579662.html|title=PopMatters|last=Pitter|first=Charles}}</ref>\n\nLowery is critical of the internet era and states that things might be worse for working musicians than under the old record system. In 2012, he gave a widely shared talk called \"Meet the new boss, worse than the old boss\"<ref name=\"Durkin2014\">{{cite book|first=Andrew|last=Durkin|title=Decomposition: A Music Manifesto|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_wSjAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT276|date=18 November 2014|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-91176-6|page=276}}</ref><ref name=\"wnyc\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/274597-meet-new-boss-worse-old-boss/ | title=Meet the New Boss, Worse Than the Old Boss - On The Media | work=WNYC | accessdate=2 May 2016 | author=Lowery, David}}</ref> in which he criticized [[Pandora Radio]] for low songwriter royalties, claiming to have made less than $17 from a million streams of his song \"[[Low (Cracker song)|Low]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.salon.com/2014/08/31/david_lowery_heres_how_pandora_is_destroying_musicians/|title=David Lowery: Here's how Pandora is destroying musicians|last=Timberg|first=Scott|date=August 31, 2014|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Lowery settled a lawsuit against [[Napster]], which concerned unpaid mechanical royalties.<ref>https://www.digitalmusicnews.com/2019/01/17/napster-settles-david-lowery-lawsuit</ref>\n\n==Discography (solo)==\n* ''The Palace Guards'' (2011)\n* ''Conquistador'' (2016)\n* ''In The Shadow of the Bull'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|David Lowery (musician)|David Lowery}}\n* [http://300songs.com/ David Lowery's \"300 Songs\" Blog]\n* [http://radio-va.com/ RadioVA]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061210151432/http://mog.com/david_lowery David Lowery's personal blog and music collection at MOG.com]\n* [https://archive.org/details/DavidLowery David Lowery collection] at the [[Internet Archive]]'s live music archive\n* [https://archive.org/details/Cracker Cracker collection] at the [[Internet Archive]]'s live music archive\n* [http://popgurls.com/2006/06/04/popgurls-interview-david-lowery-of-cracker-and-camper-van-beethoven/ PopGurls Interview: David Lowery]\n\n{{Camper_Van_Beethoven}}\n{{Cracker}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lowery, David}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American derivatives traders]]\n[[Category:American financial analysts]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:American music publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Texas]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Singers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:University of Georgia faculty]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Camper Van Beethoven members]]\n[[Category:Cracker (band) members]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                  = David Lowery\n| image                 = David Lowery.jpg\n| background            = solo_singer\n| birth_name            = David Charles Lowery\n| alias                 = \n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|1960|9|10}}\n| birth_place           = [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Texas]]<br />[[United States]]\n| death_date            = \n| instrument            = [[Singing|Vocals]]<br/>[[Guitar]]\n| genre                 = [[Alternative rock]], [[southern rock]], [[alternative country]], [[country music|country]]\n| occupation            = Lecturer UG\n| years_active          = 1983\u2013present\n| label                 = [[429 Records|429]] \n| associated_acts       = [[Camper Van Beethoven]]<br />[[Cracker (band)|Cracker]]\n| Education             = Doctorate  5-4-18  University of Georgia\n| website               = \n}}\n\n'''David Charles Lowery''' (born September 10, 1960) is an [[United States|American]] guitarist, vocalist, songwriter, and mathematician. He is the founder of [[alternative rock]] band [[Camper Van Beethoven]] and co-founder of the more-traditional rock band [[Cracker (band)|Cracker]]. Lowery released his first solo album, ''The Palace Guards'', on February 2, 2011, via the [[429 Records]] label.<ref name=\"429 Records1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.429records.com/sites/429records/aboutus.asp|title=About Us|year=2013|work=429 Records imprint from The Savoy Label Group (SLG), a division of Columbia Music Entertainment|publisher=429 Records Santa Monica. CA|accessdate=7 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618185217/http://www.429records.com/sites/429records/aboutus.asp|archive-date=18 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Personal life and music career===\nLowery was born in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Texas]], the son of a career [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] father. He has described his parents as \"a hillbilly and an English working-class woman.\"<ref name=fricke>{{cite magazine |last1=Fricke |first1=David |author-link1=David Fricke|date=19 May 1988|title=Camper Van Beethoven's Notes from the Underground |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/camper-van-beethovens-notes-from-the-underground-82927/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=8 November 2018 }}</ref> His family moved around a great deal during his youth before finally settling in [[Redlands, California]], where he attended high school. He became involved in music as a member of the band Sitting Ducks, who played a mixture of [[punk rock|punk]] and [[acid rock]], along with what Lowery described as \"fake Russian-sounding music.\" Sitting Ducks subsequently evolved into Camper Van Beethoven, formed in 1983 in [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/david-lowery-mn0000808839/biography | title=David Lowery | work=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=28 March 2014 | author=Deming, Mark}}</ref><ref name=fricke /> The band is best known for its cover of the [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]] song \"[[Pictures of Matchstick Men]]\" from the ''[[Key Lime Pie (album)|Key Lime Pie]]'' LP and its original composition \"[[Take the Skinheads Bowling]],\" from the band's 1985 debut LP, ''[[Telephone Free Landslide Victory]],'' later featured in the [[Michael Moore]] movie ''[[Bowling for Columbine]].''\n\nIn the early 1990s, Lowery formed Cracker with guitarist and long-time friend [[Johnny Hickman]] and bassist [[Davey Faragher]]. Cracker rejected the indie-rock sound of Camper Van Beethoven in favor of a more traditional, roots-rock sound. Cracker's biggest hits are \"Teen Angst (What the World Needs Now)\" from its [[Cracker (album)|eponymous LP]], released in 1992, and \"Low,\" from 1993's ''[[Kerosene Hat]].'' Cracker continues to perform today, although Camper Van Beethoven has also reformed, releasing a cover of the entire [[Fleetwood Mac]] album ''[[Tusk (album)|Tusk]]'' in 2002 and several new albums of original music, beginning with ''[[New Roman Times]]'' in 2004.\n\n[[File:David Lowery 03.jpg|thumb|left|David Lowery attending a book reading in 2011]]\nLowery has also done work as a producer at [[Sound of Music Studios]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]], working on records by [[Sparklehorse]], [[Counting Crows]], [[Lauren Hoffman]], [[September 67]], [[Wormburner]], [[LP (singer)|LP]], [[Tea Leaf Green]], [[Magnet (musician)|Magnet]], [[Sons of Bill]] and others. Lowery, along with Ian Solla-Yates of [[WNRN]] started RadioVA with Sound of Music in May 2010, an interview program hosted by David that has featured [[The Hold Steady]], [[Drive-By Truckers]], [[Minus the Bear]] and [[Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros]].\n\nOn September 13, 2010, David married Velena Vego. Vego has been the manager for both Cracker and Camper Van Beethoven since 2004. She is also the talent booker for the [[40 Watt Club]] in Athens, Georgia, and [[Buckhead Theatre]] in Atlanta.\n\n=== Other activities ===\nLowery is a trained [[mathematician]] who has worked as a \"[[quantitative analyst|quant]]\" (a [[derivative (finance)|derivatives]] trader and [[financial analyst]]) and has started a number of music-related businesses, including a [[recording studio|studio]], a [[record company]] and a [[Music publisher (popular music)|publishing company]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://thetrichordist.wordpress.com/2012/04/15/meet-the-new-boss-worse-than-the-old-boss-full-post/\n| work=The Trichordist\n| title=Meet the New Boss, Worse Than the Old Boss\n| date=April 15, 2012\n}}</ref>\nLowery's extensive experience in business led to his appointment as a lecturer in the [[University of Georgia]]'s music business program.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |last        = Miller\n |first       = Chris\n |date        = February 1, 2011\n |title       = TAKING NOTES: Rock star becomes University music professor\n |url         = http://www.redandblack.com/2011/02/01/taking-notes-rockstar-becomes-university-music-professor/\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110205125321/http://www.redandblack.com/2011/02/01/taking-notes-rockstar-becomes-university-music-professor/\n |archivedate = 2011-02-05\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/188835-cracker-berkeley-to-bakersfield-2495579662.html: \" in addition to this work, Lowery teaches as a lecturer and, as already mentioned, has a consistently high profile in the media as a champion of artists' rights. As such, it could almost be said that Lowery has become the voice of a generation\"|title=PopMatters|last=Pitter|first=Charles|website=PopMatters}}</ref>\n\nLowery earned a PhD from the University of Georgia in 2018. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Charles Pitter at PopMatters has said that \"in addition to this work, Lowery teaches as a lecturer and has a consistently high profile in the media as a champion of artists rights. As such, it could almost be said that Lowery has become the voice of a generation; however, it seems likely he would dismiss this title as meaningless blabber.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/188835-cracker-berkeley-to-bakersfield-2495579662.html|title=PopMatters|last=Pitter|first=Charles}}</ref>\n\nLowery is critical of the internet era and states that things might be worse for working musicians than under the old record system. In 2012, he gave a widely shared talk called \"Meet the new boss, worse than the old boss\"<ref name=\"Durkin2014\">{{cite book|first=Andrew|last=Durkin|title=Decomposition: A Music Manifesto|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_wSjAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT276|date=18 November 2014|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-91176-6|page=276}}</ref><ref name=\"wnyc\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/274597-meet-new-boss-worse-old-boss/ | title=Meet the New Boss, Worse Than the Old Boss - On The Media | work=WNYC | accessdate=2 May 2016 | author=Lowery, David}}</ref> in which he criticized [[Pandora Radio]] for low songwriter royalties, claiming to have made less than $17 from a million streams of his song \"[[Low (Cracker song)|Low]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.salon.com/2014/08/31/david_lowery_heres_how_pandora_is_destroying_musicians/|title=David Lowery: Here's how Pandora is destroying musicians|last=Timberg|first=Scott|date=August 31, 2014|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Lowery settled a lawsuit against [[Napster]], which concerned unpaid mechanical royalties.<ref>https://www.digitalmusicnews.com/2019/01/17/napster-settles-david-lowery-lawsuit</ref>\n\n==Discography (solo)==\n* ''The Palace Guards'' (2011)\n* ''Conquistador'' (2016)\n* ''In The Shadow of the Bull'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|David Lowery (musician)|David Lowery}}\n* [http://300songs.com/ David Lowery's \"300 Songs\" Blog]\n* [http://radio-va.com/ RadioVA]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061210151432/http://mog.com/david_lowery David Lowery's personal blog and music collection at MOG.com]\n* [https://archive.org/details/DavidLowery David Lowery collection] at the [[Internet Archive]]'s live music archive\n* [https://archive.org/details/Cracker Cracker collection] at the [[Internet Archive]]'s live music archive\n* [http://popgurls.com/2006/06/04/popgurls-interview-david-lowery-of-cracker-and-camper-van-beethoven/ PopGurls Interview: David Lowery]\n\n{{Camper_Van_Beethoven}}\n{{Cracker}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lowery, David}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American derivatives traders]]\n[[Category:American financial analysts]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:American music publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Texas]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Singers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:University of Georgia faculty]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Camper Van Beethoven members]]\n[[Category:Cracker (band) members]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Catseatsbirds",